Introduction¶

This data analysis report select 'FBI Gun Data set'. The two data files are 'gun_data.xlsx' and 'u.s.-census-data.csv'. gun_data.xlsx include the number of firearm checks by month, state, and type (recorded by NICS)
u.s.-census-data.csv contains variables at the state level. Most variables just have one data

This report answer the following questions:

1) What census data is most associated with high gun per capita?

2) Which states have had the highest growth in gun registrations?

3) What is the overall trend of gun purchases?

Observation 1 - for gun_data: The data are collected over the years for all the states. All the rows are unique and there are lots of null values and 0 values.
Observation 2 - for census data: the census data file collect different kind of data for all the states. We can use the relavent population data to calculate #of check per Capita (which is related to #of check per 1000 people). Also there are some notes and cell with characters in numeric columns and we need to clean them. Also census data need to be transposed to match gun_data in order to do statistical calulations
Observation 3 - for both data: It seems census data only have two month of population are related to gun_data. Also the number of states are slightly different and hence some states in gun_data needs to be dropped as well

Data Cleaning¶

for gun_data set: since there are lots of nulls and 0s for some of the columns in gun data set. It is a good idea to just fill all the null values to 0.

Data Cleaning¶

for census data::
1) drop column 'Fact Note'
2) drop rows from 64 and beyond since that are all notes, and has nothing to do with stats calculation
3) rename column 'Fact' to 'state' for gun per capita calculation and plot display
4) Transpose census data to match gun data format for easy plotting
5) fix column name, and data content (such as 'D', 'F' etc)
6) replace ',' as '' to reform the numbers (e.g. 4,500 to 4500), remove % for column represented in %, removed \$ sign for numbers that represents currency

Conclusions¶

From all the descriptive statistic above, we can see gun per capita increased dramatically between 2010-04 and 2016-07 for most of the states. It seems no information in census data is directly related to the high gun capita. Among all the states, Indiana has the highest increase in percentage while Kentuky has the absolute highest number of arms per capita of the nation
